Hi Jess, 

Thanks for this, we have done some investigation and my theory was correct. Because the email blast is linked directly to the PDF file, Google Analytics (GA) is bypassed. The only way to 'count' the downloads would be to send them to a page on the site (this would count as a visit in GA) and then to link the PDF to a button (this would count as a download event in GA). 

I hope this makes sense? Let me know if you would prefer to chat through it?

Hi Heath,

I have just emailed you from admin@msaustralia.org.au the email that was sent out that included the Strategic Plan pdf.

Let me know how you go with this.

Kind regards,

Hi Jess, 

Sorry for the delay in getting back to you on this one. Are you able to send me a copy of the email that was sent out? It will help me to better see what is happening. 

I suspect that when linking directly to the PDF, that GA is not tracking it as a webpage has not been viewed... A PDF has been viewed. There will be no way for GA to 'see' this. But, that being said, please do send the email to heath@wolfiq.com.au and I will test.

Hi Heath,

Hope you are well!

We have just been looking at our website analytics and in particular the results of the strategic plan downloads on GA.

We're seeing a discrepancy between the downloads for this pdf on GA vs our Campaign Monitor where the pdf was included in an EDM and we received 993 link clicks directly to the pdf on our website. Are you able to please have a look at this to check if we are tracking this properly on GA? Or would this appear somewhere else if its directly from the EDM send?

Kind regards,

Jess

Yes, that's 100% correct. Once you add a new PDF it will automatically be tracked. But, I always recommend adding it a couple of days prior to a big launch or email blast and testing that the tracking is working as expected.
